shows why this civil religious tradition is now in peril—and with it the American experiment.American Covenant traces the history of prophetic republicanism from the Puritan era to today, providing insightful portraits of figures ranging from John Winthrop and W.E.B. Du Bois to Jerry Falwell, Ronald Reagan, and Barack Obama. Featuring a new preface by the author, this incisive book demonstrates how half a century of culture war has drowned out the quieter voices of the vital center, and demonstrates that if we are to rebuild that center, we must recover the civil religious tradition on which the republic was founded.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican civil religion.  aAmerican exceptionalism.  aAmericans.  aApocalypticism.  aAristocracy.  aAtheism.  aBarack Obama.  aCalvinism.  aCambridge University Press.  aChristian ethics.  aChristian nationalism.  aChristian theology.  aChristianity.  aCivic nationalism.  aCivic virtue.  aCivil religion.  aClassical liberalism.  aClassical republicanism.  aCommon good.  aConstitutional patriotism.  aCotton Mather.  aCovenant theology.  aCulture war.  aDeism.  aDemocracy.  aDemonization.  aDoctrine.  aElection.  aFreedom of religion.  aFreedom of speech.  aGod.  aGood and evil.  aGovernance.  aGovernment.  aH. L. Mencken.  aHannah Arendt.  aHeresy.  aHeterodoxy.  aIdeology.  aIdolatry.  aImperialism.  aIndividualism.  aInstitution.  aJane Addams.  aJeremiad.  aJerry Falwell.  aJews.  aJohn Courtney Murray.  aJohn Locke.  aJohn Winthrop.  aJudeo-Christian.  aLiberal democracy.  aLiberalism.  aLiberty.  aMilitarism.  aMillennialism.  aModernity.  aNarrative.  aNew Atheism.  aNonbeliever.  aOld Testament.  aOliga